Most men don't call it anxiety. They call it pressure, or stress, or "just how I'm wired." But it looks like this: a mind that runs every worst-case scenario before breakfast. A chest that stays tight through the weekend. Snapping at your kids because your nervous system has been at DEFCON 2 since Tuesday. Lying awake doing math on everything that could go wrong.

You can white-knuckle a season like that. A lot of men white-knuckle a decade.

## What's actually going on

Anxiety isn't weakness and it isn't a character flaw — it's an alarm system that's stuck in the on position. Usually it started doing a job for you a long time ago: staying vigilant kept something bad from happening, or at least it felt that way. The problem is the alarm never learned to shut off, and now it's running your schedule, your stomach, and half your decisions.

## How counseling helps

In our work together, we'll do two things at once. First, the practical: understanding how anxiety operates in your body and your week, and building real tools for the moments it spikes. Second, the deeper work: getting at the story underneath the vigilance — what you're bracing for, where you learned to brace, and what it would mean to trust God with outcomes you can't control.

That second part matters. "Do not be anxious" was never meant as a command to try harder. It's an invitation to put weight down on something that can actually hold it. Getting there is a process — and it's exactly the work we'll do.

## When to reach out

If the worry has started costing you sleep, patience, focus, or presence with your family — that's enough. You don't need a diagnosis or a breaking point to justify the call.
